column1: #Text=Monday , following her return from London , Wikinews talked with Amanda Carter , the longest-serving member of Australia 's national wheelchair basketball team ( the Gliders ) .
#Text=It says here that you spent your childhood living in Banyule ?
#Text=City of Banyule , but I was West Heidelberg .
#Text=And you used to play netball when you were young ?
#Text=And you 're an occupational therapist , and you have a son called Alex ?
#Text=It says " occupational therapist " on the door even .

column1: #Text=And I do have a son called Alex .
#Text=Which is him there [ pointing to his picture ] .
#Text=And that you are a one point player .
#Text=And you used to be a two point player ?
#Text=I used to be a two point player .
#Text=When were you first selected for the national team ?
#Text=It was for a tournament prior to then .
#Text=Australia had to qualify at a pre- Paralympic tournament in England in about April of 1992 and I was selected for that .
#Text=And that was my first trip overseas with the Gliders .
#Text=We won that tournament , which qualified us for Barcelona .
#Text=I guess because it was my first Paralympics .
#Text=I had n't long been in a wheelchair , so all of it was pretty new to me .
#Text=I guess Australia was n't expected to do very well and finished fourth , so it was a good tournament for us .
#Text=Did you play with a club as well ?
#Text=I played in the men 's league at that point .
#Text=It had a different name back then .
#Text=I ca n't remember what they were called back then but eventually it became the Dandenong Rangers .
#Text=' Cause 1998 was Sydney , so I 've got a feeling that it was in Stoke Mandeville in England .
#Text=Lost to the Unites States in the bronze medal game in front of a crowd of 5,000 .
